Package structure

Class HttpBody

java.lang.Object
java.util.AbstractMap<K,​V>
java.util.HashMap<java.lang.Object,​java.lang.Object>
structure.HttpBody
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.util.Map<java.lang.Object,​java.lang.Object>
public final class HttpBody
extends java.util.HashMap<java.lang.Object,​java.lang.Object>
This is a custom HashMap class for fluently and elegantly writing and reading values in JSON.

Originally, using a HashMap/ArrayList would always bother developers by having TypeCasting warnings/exceptions, and also make the code less readable. This class is to perfectly avoid.

Though it extends from HashMap, developers are allowed to make it perform a List.

Since:
Kanban 2.0

    • hasValue

      public boolean hasValue​(java.lang.Object value)
      This is a syntatic sugar.

      Returns true if the instance maps one or more keys to the specified value. More formally, returns true if and only if the instance contains at least one mapping to a value v such that Objects.equals(value, v). This operation will probably require time linear in the map size for most implementations of the Map interface.

      Parameters:
      value - value whose presence in this instance is to be tested
      Returns:
      true if the instance maps one or more keys to the specified value false if the instance maps no key to the specified value or an exception is thrown

    • hasKey

      public boolean hasKey​(java.lang.Object key)
      This is a syntatic sugar.

      Returns true if the instance contains a mapping for the specified key. More formally, returns true if and only if the instance contains a mapping for a key k such that Objects.equals(key, k). (There can be at most one such mapping.)

      Parameters:
      key - key whose presence in this instance is to be tested
      Returns:
      true if the instance contains a mapping for the specified key false if the instance maps no key to the specified value or an exception is thrown
